{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17719"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17719"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72327"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57797"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10166"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24488"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72327"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESpecialised sensory receptors in human skin allow for precise discrimination of various tactile stimuli.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of Meissner\u0027s corpuscles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Detection of sustained pressure","Detection of tissue damage","Detection of temperature changes","Detection of light touch and vibration","Detection of joint position"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of light touch and vibration\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of Meissner\u0027s corpuscles. These specialised mechanoreceptors are located in the dermal papillae of glabrous (hairless) skin and are particularly abundant in areas requiring fine tactile discrimination such as fingertips, palms, and lips.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of sustained pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by Ruffini endings and Merkel cells, which are slowly adapting receptors that respond to continuous pressure.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of tissue damage\u003C/strong\u003E is mediated by nociceptors, which are free nerve endings that respond to noxious stimuli.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of temperature changes\u003C/strong\u003E is accomplished by specialised thermoreceptors that respond to either heat or cold.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of joint position\u003C/strong\u003E is achieved by proprioceptors located within muscles, tendons, and joint capsules.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeissner\u0027s corpuscles are rapidly adapting receptors, meaning they respond quickly to changes in stimuli but stop firing if the stimulus remains constant. This property makes them particularly well-suited for detecting dynamic touch sensations and vibration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meissner\u0027s corpuscles are specialised mechanoreceptors found in glabrous (hairless) skin that detect light touch and vibration.","These receptors are rapidly adapting and most densely concentrated in fingertips, palms, soles, lips, and genitalia.","Meissner\u0027s corpuscles are located in the dermal papillae just beneath the epidermis."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57797"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17719"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57797"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T07:35:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T07:36:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10433"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72327"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Skin and A